   "id": "33257a8d-e07f-4001-849f-8c72ad9b28b3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Difference Between List and Tuple in Python\n",
    "\n",
    "| Feature     | List                        | Tuple                     |\n",
    "| ----------- | --------------------------- | ------------------------- |\n",
    "| Mutability  | Mutable (can change)        | Immutable (cannot change) |\n",
    "| Syntax      | `[ ]`                       | `( )`                     |\n",
    "| Performance | Slower                      | Faster                    |\n",
    "| Memory      | More memory                 | Less memory               |\n",
    "| Methods     | Many (append, remove, etc.) | Few (count, index)        |\n",
    "| Use Case    | Dynamic data                | Fixed data                |\n",
    "Lists are mutable and dynamic, while tuples are immutable and more memory-efficient, making tuples faster and safer for fixed data."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "0e916906-45c8-4a2b-9e16-a9ff89c8e300",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "🔹 What is MCP in Agentic AI?\n",
    "\n",
    "MCP = Model Context Protocol\n",
    "\n",
    "It is a standard way for AI agents to access external tools, data, and context in a structured manner.\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 Simple Explanation\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 MCP acts like a bridge between:\n",
    "\n",
    "AI model (LLM)\n",
    "\n",
    "External systems (APIs, databases, tools)\n",
    "\n",
    "So the agent can:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Fetch data\n",
    "\n",
    "- Use tools\n",
    "\n",
    "- Maintain context"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "b4dfcd36-ea58-4ef9-90d9-f9d662c39581",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Question: \n",
    "How do you retrieve data using a pickled machine learning model stored in an AWS S3 bucket? Additionally, if you are receiving real-time data that is being stored in a database on AWS, how would you handle data processing and integration in that scenario?\n",
    "\n",
    "Answer:\n",
    "I load the pickled model from S3 using boto3 and deserialize it using pickle. For real-time systems, I don’t use S3 as a database; instead, I use RDS or DynamoDB for real-time access and keep S3 for storage and batch processing. The model is loaded once in memory for low-latency predictions, and results or logs are stored back in S3."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "5ab92a0c-df0c-4017-9dbc-5f3425629070",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
